We recommended that Management take the following courses of action:

Ensure continued prompt remittance to the  GSIS of the monthly contributions (Government and Personal Share), loan amortizations, and employee compensation premium;
Through the Authorized Agency Officer (AAO), timely manifest in writing to the GSIS the need to resolve the recurring concern where its electronic bill is not updated despite LGU’s diligence in the timely updating of employee service records; 
Ensure compliance with Sections 5 and 6(b) of Republic Act (R.A.) No. 8291.

We recommended that Management take the following courses of action:

Conduct the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) mandatory review, in case of failed biddings;
Strictly comply with the required invitation to at least three suppliers, contractors or consultants, as the case maybe, for negotiated procurement under two failed biddings;
Ensure to conduct the negotiation stage in accordance with the rules prescribed in Annex H of 2016 R-IRR of R.A. No. 9184; and
Strengthen internal control measures to ensure the compliance of the LGU to all the relevant requirements mandated by 2016 R-IRR of R.A. No. 9184 for all modes of procurement.

We recommended that Management do the following courses of action:

Ensure that the Annual Budget is approved within the period prescribed in the LGC and Local Budget Operations Manual;

Ensure judicious prioritization of the 20 per cent DF by warranting that the preliminary requirements for the proposed projects are prepared and completed first before or immediately after the funds are appropriated for such projects such as the following:

Necessary Plans;
Identification of the project to be implemented;
Identification of project location;
Securing ownership of the identified project location; and
Ability to immediately provide the committed Barangay counterpart
Consider the competitiveness of rates offered to the skilled/unskilled laborers in order to address manpower unavailability; 
Follow-up the appeal made to the Environmental Management Bureau (EMB) regarding the proposed location of the Sanitary Landfill (Small Category);
Submit to the Commission on Audit (COA) the approved time extension and/or  suspension order and its supporting documents, as the case maybe, issued to the contractors, if any, in accordance with COA Circular No. 2009-001, for review and evaluation why the related disbursement transactions will not be suspended in audit; and
Guarantee that the 20 per cent of the Internal Revenue Allotment (IRA) is optimally utilized as prescribed in Department of Budget and Management-Department of Interior and Local Government (DBM-DILG) Joint Memorandum Circular (JMC) No. 2017-01.

We recommended that the Management take the following courses of action:

For future projects to be funded by the LGSF-AM and other NGA programs, ensure LGU’s compliance on the following:
During the proposal stage, correctly identify and classify the proposed project location, such as in case of road upgrading project whether barangay or municipal road, to ensure that corresponding requirements based on existing standards (such as required measure Road ROW) pertaining thereto will be followed and related documents will be prepared accordingly;
Ensure that issues or problems encountered during the preparation of documents required for the project, such as those arising from securing ROW, are prioritized and resolved timely; 
Direct each concerned unit/office within the LGU to promptly take appropriate actions with regard to the documents to be prepared by each of the said unit/office in relation to the requirements of the project for its timely submission; and
Follow-up timely the documents coming from other concerned NGAs which are required for the project;
For the AM 2019 project of Local Access Road Upgrading in Barangay Sta. Cruz, ensure compliance with the Project Implementation Schedule for the timely completion of the project; and;
Revisit and evaluate the LGU’s compliance with the provisions of DILG MC No. 2019-71 on the implementation of AM 2019 project. In case of inadvertently overlooked non-compliance, promptly take the appropriate actions as necessary and in accordance with the said guidelines.

We recommended that Management take the following courses of actions:

Adjust the RPT/SET Receivables and their Deferred Income Accounts to reflect the actual unpaid RPT dues from CYs 1991 to present provided by the Municipal Assessor and Municipal Treasurer; 

Eventually include the unpaid RPT dues from CYs 1990 and below through manual verification and computation to reflect accurately total RPT/SET Receivables.

We recommended that Management take the following courses of action:

The concerned Implementing Units of these BUB/GPB projects ensure to update the Accounting Unit regarding the status of these projects. Should some of these projects had already been completed, submit to the said Unit the certification confirming such fact to enable the Accounting Unit and other concerned Office (such as the Municipal Treasurer’s Office) to take appropriate actions relating to the balance of fund transfer from the SA in accordance with COA Circular No. 94-013. With regard to the savings relating to the LGU counterpart, ensure compliance with Section 418, IRR of the LGC to enable the reversion of these funds to the General Fund;

With regard to the completed projects, ensure complying with the required and needed documents to warrant the prompt processing of the payment to the concerned suppliers or, at least, ensure the accrual of such obligations, when warranted;

Conduct timely the procurement activities to ensure completion of the projects in accordance with its scheduled implementation;

The LGU as a whole should consider projects proposed to be funded by different NGAs under different programs, such that of the BUB/GPB, though few, will have enough funding allocation to ensure its impact to the intended beneficiaries;

The LGU, primarily the LCE and the LPRAT, should ensure monitoring of these BUB/GPB projects to guarantee its completion.

